MissionCommands.Message: Welcome to the ascent lesson! This is an advanced lesson with multiple parts that are considered hard, and might require a few attempts. We are mostly going off-checklist today, with manual control during docking in both crafts.
To get started, please enter the LM using F4. As you can see, you are currently on the lunar surface. The CSM is in a circular orbit above you and the LM is almost ready for ascent.
Our job today is to use the Ascent Propulsion System to ascend into an elliptical orbit around the Moon, before rendezvousing and docking with the CSM.
We are still attached to the Descent Stage, and using its systems. As we start our ascent, we will separate from it, so we need to configure our systems for that.
There are some checklists available for doing this procedurally correct, but for now we will just connect the normal ascent batteries, and deadface the descent batteries.
Set ASCENT BAT 5 NORMAL to ON, the talkback should indicate gray.
Set ASCENT BAT  6 NORMAL to ON, the talkback should indicate gray.
The ASCENT stage is now also powering our systems. To disable the descent batteries, set the DES BAT switch to DEADFACE.
The ASCENT stage is now powering the entire module.
Normally, this is done closer to the ascent time, but we need the time to describe the process. The most important thing here is that you learn the major things needed.
The CSM is currently orbiting the moon, and our ignition time is set to around 70 seconds after it passes this launch area.
Let's request the ignition time from MCC. Open the comm menu, and REQUEST ASCENT.
This will give us the time of ignition.
The ascent time is quite far ahead as I thought it would be good for you to read through the STAGING checklists, as well as the LUNAR ASCENT checklists.
This is just for you to get familiar with the realistic procedures, and what's ahead. Also, you should read the BRIEFING part of the Mission Pad.
When you are ready, press ROGER to go to the next step.

Let's set up the DAP for the ascent. I assume you are familiar with how to do this now. Use V48E and set the DAP to +12102 using V21E +12102E. Press ROGER when you have complete the DAP setup routine.
Program 12 is the LGC program used for ascent. Key V37E 12E to start it,
P12 will first show us the MET of ignition. Press PRO to accept.
Noun 76 will show us the planned insertion values. Press PRO.
We are now counting down to ignition. Set S/C ROLL to MODE CONT.
Set S/C PITCH to MODE CONT.
Set S/C YAW to MODE CONT.
The PGNS is now in control of the spacecraft, and P12 will guide it into the correct orbit.
Next we will prepare the ascent engine and pressurize it for ascent.
On the ED, set MASTER ARM to ON.
Then pressurize the APS with Helium by setting He PRESS ASCENT to FIRE.
Next we will need to let the helium flow to the ascent engine. Set the ASC He valve to OPEN.
Set the MODE SEL switch to PGNS to let the tape instruments be guided by the PGNS system, instead of the Landing Radar.
Then ARM the ascent engine by setting the ENG ARM to ASC.
For ignition to correctly happen, the ED will need to be on. We will keep the ED armed during our preparations. But please note that this is typically done close to ignition.
Use timescale to fast forward to about 10 minutes before ignition. Press ROGER when you have done so.
Upon APS ignition, with the ED being armed, staging from the descent stage will automatically happen. However, we need to update the AGS about the staging sequence.
This is done by pressing ABORT STAGE. In the current configuration, this will set up the AGS for staging, just in case.
Pay attention to the timer when we get close to launch. At 35 seconds, the registers will blank for 5 seconds.
Press PRO when V99 shows to commit the ignition of the APS.
Liftoff!
Pay attention to the altitude and altitude rate tapes. It should be increasing.
After about 5 seconds, guidance will pitch down to start building the orbital velocity needed for insertion.
Time to insertion is about 7 to 8 minutes. In the bottom of the P12 ascent checklist you will find the ascent cue card. Use this as a reference during ascent.
Once we get into orbit, we will need to use the rendezvous radar to find the CSM, then start planning for our first burn: The CSI burn.
Pay attention to the instruments as you are ascending, and try to stay on top of the trajectory and the procedures. Lets prepare for RCS control, set the THROTTLE/JETS switch to JETS.
Then set ENG THRUST CONTROL from MAN to AUTO. This enables RCS translational control in all axed, something we need on insertion.
We won't be needing the APS engine after insertion, so close to cutoff, we will allow its remaining fuel to be used by the RCS system.
Set SYSTEM A: ASC FUEL to ASC FEED 1.
Set SYSTEM A: ASC OXID to ASC FEED 2.
Set SYSTEM B: ASC FUEL to ASC FEED 1.
Set SYSTEM B: ASC OXIDto ASC FEED 2.
The APS is now allowing RCS to spend its fuel.
Cutoff.  Use the orbital view to verify if your orbit is aligned and in-plane with the CSM.
This completes the first part of the academy, namely the ascent. For the reminder of the rendezvous we will use the RCS, and not the APS.
Our next job is to find the CSM. To do this, we will use the rendezvous radar, and then use P20 to let guidance maneuver the LM into a line-of-sight attitude.
Set RNG/ALT MON to RNG/RNG RT.
Close the AC BUS A: RNDZ RDR so the RR motor get AC power so it can turn.
On the LGC, press PRO until P12 automatically starts P00.
Use the [C]ommunication menu to open the co-pilot view, press RENDEZVOUS RADAR SLEW from the menu, and press REQUEST.

This will let the LMP tell us the direction we need to slew the rendezvous radar to target the CSM. Use CTRL+Arrow Keys (default mapping) to slew the shaft/trunnion to 0. You might need to maneuver the spacecraft manually to prograde if the angles are large.
You will notice that the NO TRACK light extinguishes, and that the RADAR signal gauge increases. Set the RR selector to AUTO TRACK.
Use the co-pilot menu to disable the RR SLEW aid.
The RR will now track the CSM, and provide data. We need to allow it to update the state vector, and to orient the LM so we are facing it.
On the LGC, Key V37E 20E
Noun72 will show you the shaft and trunnion angles. We need to zero these to face the CSM. Press PRO.
Noun 49 shows the data from the RR. Press PRO.
Then press PRO again. The PGNS will now try to keep it's orientation so we are facing the CSM.
Press PRO until P20 starts P00.
Set the LTG: EXTERIOR LTG to TRACK. Our tracking light will start flashing, and should be visible from the CSM.
Our next burn is the CSI burn. To plan this, we need to use P30, and to execute the burn, we will use P41.
Start by requesting the burn parameters from MCC by using the REQUEST CSI from the [C]omm menu.
When the parameters are received, start P30 by keying V37E 30E
P30 will first show us the MET of ignition. Press PRO.
N81 will show us the dV in local vertical. Press PRO.
N42 will spend a few seconds calculating, before showing the estimated orbit after the burn. It should be a circular orbit, and the values are in nmi altitude. Press PRO.
N45 shows the countdown to the burn. P41 will not have any signs of when ignition should happen, and is completely manual. It is therefore very important to set up the event timer.
Ensure the event timer is set to 00:00 and not counting.
Then slew the MIN UNIT so the event timer shows 05:00 (5 minutes), and set the COUNT direction to DOWN.
Set the ORDEAL FDAI 1 to ORB RATE.
Then set the ATTITUDE MODE CONTROL to ATT HOLD.
Manuever so the FDAI has a prograde attitude with 0 roll. FDAI should read about 0,0,0. The attitude can be anything really, as the RCS can burn in any direction.
If the PGNS is giving you issues, you can set it to OFF and maneuver manual.
When the LGC shows exactly 5 minutes left to the burn, start the EVENT TIMER so it counts down, and press PRO. Verify P00 and that the event timer is counting down.
Start P41 by keying V37E 41E.
Press PRO to accept auto-maneuver.
The PRO to see N85.
N85 is key for the burn, and will give you the information you need. You will use the RCS jets to translate the LM.
N85 shows the amount to delta-V still required in each LM body axis to reach the target velocity set by P30. If you are facing exactly prograde, only one of the registers will have a value.
These values will change based on what attitude you have, and shows the dV in fps with two decimals. If R3 shows +04100, the burn requires 41.00 fps in that axis.
When the event timer reaches 00:00, our burn should begin, and you need to translate to zero the values.
When the body axis values shows about zero in each axis, the burn is complete. Please note that errors might accumulate based on when ignition happened and how quickly the burn was executed.
CSI complete when values are close to zero. At that point, stop and reset the event timer, and set it to 5 minutes again.
Press PRO until P41 starts P00.
We are now in a circular orbit, slowly catching up on the CSM. The LM RR should be tracking the CSM, but if not, you need to slew it again so it starts tracking.
Enter the CSM, set the CMC MODE from FREE to AUTO, and key V37E 79E.
Press PRO to accept automaneuvering. This will orient the CSM so it faces the LM. Return to the LM.
The next burn is the TPI burn. It will set us on rendezvous trajectory with the CSM. Please note that this is the simplified rendezvous, and this burn will be a Hohmann-burn.
From the [C]omm menu, REQUEST TPI.
This burn is very similar to our previous burn, and will take us into a more elliptical orbit, with Ap at the point where the CSM is at the time we reach it.
With the parameters received, run P30 again and set it up.
When the countdown reaches 5 minutes, start the event timer so it counts down, and if the NO TRACK light is illuminated, slew the RR to reacquire the CSM.
Don't forget the time, but you should now be close enough so the CSM can see the flashing tracking light.
Run P41 and prepare for the burn. N85 should once again show the body axis velocities needed for the burn. Use ATT HOLD or your preferred mode and try to orient so the values show a prograde burn.
Again, this is not needed, but makes it easier and quicker. Precision is key.
When the burn is complete, you are on a rendezvous trajectory to the CSM, and it will be closing in above you, and from the CSM, the LM will be approaching from below.
While coasting, let's set up the CSM. Enter the CSM, and verify that the docking probe is ready for docking. In addition, check that the attitude is OK, so we are facing the LM. Correct as needed.
Also, use the tools/comm menu to insert the docking target in the right CSM rendezvous window, just like the COAS is installed in the left CDR window.
We are getting closer and closer. Enter the CSM, and install the COAS in the left rendezvous window.
Set the EMS setting to BACKUP/VHF RNG.
Then set the EMS MODE selector to dV SET/VHF RNG. This will now show the range to the LM. It should be decreasing.
The docking we are about to perform is a CSM Active docking with the LM. This means that the docking will be done by the CSM, as the fuel levels in the LM are very limited.
For this lesson, I recommend you to set the CSM CMC mode to FREE, so you are in complete control of it's orientation. Try to keep the LM in the COAS target.

Enter the LM, we need to change our lights from TRACK to DOCK, then set the spacecraft controls to ATT HOLD or DIR for manual control. We will practice flying both spacecrafts manually at the same time.

Orient the LM so you can see the CSM through the window, and ensure your roll is 0. The tapes should now be more stable and show you the range and the closing rate. Set the RATE/ERR MON switch to RNDZ RADAR.

Press F9 to center the view on the window and center the CSM using the window marks. With the CSM centered in the window, note your FDAI pitch value. Pitch down 90 degrees from this value so the docking port is facing the CSM.
Open the view selector, and press OVERHEAD WINDOW.
Look up and find the overhead window COAS, then center the COAS on the rendezvous target in the CSM window. Attitude control is a bit harder since you are looking up and not forward, practice a bit.

Then enter the CSM, and start your docking maneuvers, but avoid translating unless absolutely necessary. The LM should be tilted 90 degrees, and the docking port and target will be visible. If not, correct in the LM.

You can try to set the LM docking target in the CSM COAS, then go back to the LM and set the CSM docking target in the LM COAS. It's usually easier to get the correct attitude by doing this instead of translating too much.

It's good practice to set up the views so that you can cycle between the CSM and the LM COAS view by just pressing F4. Cycle between and perform attitude changes to keep the docking target in the COAS, but only translate in the CSM.
Perform the docking as you are used to. But right before contact, quickly turn off the LM PGNS system and set controls to manual to avoid RCS conflicts after docking.

Congratulations, great job! You have now mastered the Lunar Module. This might require some tries before you are confident. You can re-run this lesson, and then use the ASCENT, RENDEZVOUS and DOCK missions to practice the maneuvers.

Title: Lesson 12 - Lunar Ascent & Docking
Description: You now know how to operate the Lunar Module, and how to perform a powered descent. In this lesson, we will learn how to perform an ascent from the lunar surface into lunar orbit, and how to rendezvous and dock with the CSM. Consider this an advanced lesson, and you should be very familiar with the LM and the CM before attempting this.
BriefingText:
BRIEFING

For those familiar with the Lunar Ascent and the LM/CSM rendezvous will know that this is a complex operation. There are a lot of procedures involved, and many new systems will be used. In addition, you will need to control two spacecrafts at the same time. The LM during ascent, and the rendezvous burns, and the CSM for docking, and during the rendezvous burns.

The first part of the ascent is where the Lunar Module separates from the Descent Stage and uses it as a launch pad. The APS (Ascent Propulsion System) is used to take the Lunar Module ascent stage from the lunar surface into an elliptic orbit around the Moon, with the same inclination as the CSM. The CSM is in a larger circular orbit.

The initial orbit has and Ap altitude and Pe altitude of 17km x 83km. Once the LM reaches Ap, the orbit is circularized using a burn named Co-elliptic Sequence Initiation (CSI). 

After the above, the LM is catching up with the CSM. The Lunar Module is using the rendezvous radar to track the CSM, and have an attitude that where the LM is facing the CSM, and vice versa.

We will use a simplified more direct rendezvous in this lesson, meaning after the CSI burn, a Hohmann-burn will be used to rendezvous with the CSM, followed by docking.

P30 will be used to plan the orbital maneuvers, while P41 will execute the burns using the RCS.
